 (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\gradle-model.json`)\n179: - `kotlin-analysis/analysis.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\analysis.json`)\n180: - `kotlin-analysis/locations.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\locations.json`)\n181: - `kotlin-analysis/run-report.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\run-report.json`)\n182: - `kotlin-analysis/analysis-report.md`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\analysis-report.md`)\n183: - `kotlin-analysis/planning-note.md`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\planning-note.md`)\n184: - `kotlin-analysis/source-files.json`: missing (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\source-files.json`)\n185: - `kotlin-analysis/dependency-map.json`: missing (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\dependency-map.json`)\n186: - `kotlin-analysis/compose-map.json`: missing (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\compose-map.json`)\n187: - `kotlin-analysis/navigation-map.json`: missing (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\navigation-map.json`)\n188: - `kotlin-analysis/viewmodel-map.json`: missing (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\viewmodel-map.json`)\n189: - `kotlin-analysis/repository-map.json`: missing (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\repository-map.json`)\n190: - `kotlin-analysis/flow-livedata-map.json`: missing (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\kotlin-analysis\\flow-livedata-map.json`)\n191: - `android-analysis/manifest-summary.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\manifest-summary.json`)\n192: - `android-analysis/resource-map.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\resource-map.json`)\n193: - `android-analysis/screen-map.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\screen-map.json`)\n194: - `android-analysis/view-bindings.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\view-bindings.json`)\n195: - `android-analysis/layout-tree.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\layout-tree.json`)\n196: - `android-analysis/drawable-semantics.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\drawable-semantics.json`)\n197: - `android-analysis/adapter-map.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\adapter-map.json`)\n198: - `android-analysis/data-schema.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\data-schema.json`)\n199: - `android-analysis/crud-slices.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\crud-slices.json`)\n200: - `android-analysis/backend-api-usage.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\backend-api-usage.json`)\n201: - `android-analysis/room-schema.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\room-schema.json`)\n202: - `android-analysis/retrofit-endpoints.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\retrofit-endpoints.json`)\n203: - `android-analysis/sqlite-schema.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\sqlite-schema.json`)\n204: - `android-analysis/preferences-map.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\preferences-map.json`)\n205: - `android-analysis/refresh-chains.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\refresh-chains.json`)\n206: - `android-analysis/aggregate-semantics.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\aggregate-semantics.json`)\n207: - `android-analysis/method-summaries.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\method-summaries.json`)\n208: - `android-analysis/data-flow-gaps.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\data-flow-gaps.json`)\n209: - `android-analysis/behavior-spec.md`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\behavior-spec.md`)\n210: \n211: If an input is missing, do not invent its contents. Fall back to source inspection only for the evidence needed by the current task, and report the gap.\n212: \n213: Treat Kotlin source, Gradle metadata, Compose state, ViewModel/repository flow, resources, navigation, and user-visible refresh behavior as behavior evidence. Do not translate only UI skeletons; preserve search, filtering, CRUD, persistence, selection, dialogs, bottom bars, and immediate UI update semantics.\n214: \n215: Coverage reports are a baseline for reducing functional gaps and unexplained code-scale gaps. Do not mechanically match source LoC. Instead, map current-scope critical/high source features, resources, tests, and platform integrations to target implementation, supplemental tests, platform replacement, or explicit deferred items. `source-coverage-matrix.json` is the feature status record and `platform-capability-check.json` is the target platform capability status record: use both during planning and update them during phase/repair work. The main planning session should prioritize valid `plan.md` and `plan.json`; row-level `plannedPhase` backfill may be applied by a separate post-planning records-only session after the plan contract passes. Use language-specific static analysis outputs to refine the matrix when present. If static analysis reveals a source feature missing from the matrix template, add a matrix entry with source evidence. Critical/high `implemented` entries need specific evidence: do not bulk-promote many rows with the same notes/tests/endpoints, do not rely only on root views, shell views, state classes, whole files, or grouped endpoint lists, and do not cite target tests as strong evidence unless the notes record a successful target test compile/run command. For every closed critical/high feature, record `sourceBehavior`, `targetBehavior`, `parityLevel`, and `verificationEvidence` in `source-coverage-matrix.json`; `implemented` should use `parityLevel: equivalent`, `implemented-simplified` should use `parityLevel: simplified`, and `platform-replaced` should use `parityLevel: platform-replaced`. `verification-results.json/md` is generated evidence from build/test/manual reports, but a build pass alone is not per-feature behavior verification. Critical/high `implemented-simplified` is exceptional: record what was simplified, why user-visible behavior remains acceptable, target endpoints or tests, and source/platform evidence. Critical/high deferred feat... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n216: \n217: For this workflow, direct target API evidence means the capability is callable\n218: from the HarmonyOS Cangjie target. ArkTS `.d.ts` declarations, JS APIs, native C\n219: headers/libraries, or generic HarmonyOS capability docs are useful discovery\n220: evidence, but they are not direct Cangjie evidence by themselves. If only\n221: ArkTS/native bindings are found, record the missing Cangjie binding as a\n222: concrete blocker with fallback/deferred behavior unless a Cangjie wrapper, FFI,\n223: or bridge is already part of the target architecture or explicitly planned and\n224: verified with target endpoints plus build evidence. Do not introduce the first\n225: ArkTS/JS/native bridge merely to close coverage or capability rows, and do not\n226: mark a capability `verified-direct` or upgrade a feature to equivalent solely\n227: from ArkTS/native evidence.\n228: \n229: When checking current SDK availability, search pure Cangjie declarations first:\n230: `$HOME/.cangjie-sdk/**/cangjie/api/modules` for `.cj.d` files and\n231: `$HOME/.cangjie-sdk/**/cangjie/api/lib` for matching `.cjo` libraries. Treat\n232: DevEco ETS/JS/native SDK files as secondary discovery evidence unless a\n233: Cangjie-callable binding is found or already belongs to the target architecture.\n234: \n235: Static analysis is implementation evidence, not just matrix evidence. Use it during planning to decide phase boundaries, source evidence, files/assets/dependencies, state/data flow, platform replacement points, and test strategy. Use it during phase work to locate source behavior and preserve view/page bindings, event handlers, CRUD/persistence/API paths, refresh chains, schemas, resources, tests, and user-visible side effects. Use it during build or coverage repair to avoid deleting source-covered behavior merely to satisfy the compiler. When static analysis is incomplete or conflicts with source code, inspect the minimal relevant source files and follow the source code.\n236: \n237: Deferred is a last resort, not a planning shortcut. Do not mark features deferred merely because they are large, tedious, or inconvenient for compilation. Prefer faithful implementation; if exact parity is impossible, use the closest working implementation that preserves user-visible behavior and records the simplification reason; if platform capability differs, use a real HarmonyOS/Cangjie replacement. Use fallback or deferred only when a concrete blocker remains, such as unavailable HarmonyOS/Cangjie SDK capability, external service credentials, hardware/device dependency, legal/security constraint, or human product decision. Avoid bulk-deferred entries with repeated generic reasons.\n238: \n239: For ArkTS projects, prefer `arkts-analysis/compiler-summary.json`, `arkts-analysis/compiler-planning-note.md`, and phase-relevant compiler sidecars such as `compiler/behavior-spec.md`, `compiler/refresh-chains.json`, `compiler/method-summaries.json`, and `compiler/artifacts/cangjie-mapping-hints.json` before opening the full `arkts-analysis/compiler/analysis.json`.\n240: \n241: ## Static Analysis Limits\n242: \n243: Generated static analysis inputs are aids, not complete truth. They may miss dynamic dispatch, reflection, generated code, callback wiring, resource indirection, build-variant behavior, or platform-specific side effects. Do not rely only on static analysis when source behavior is unclear or when coverage reports indicate possible omissions. Inspect the minimal relevant source files and resources before deciding to simplify, replace, or defer behavior. For Kotlin projects, pay particular attention to Compose state, remembered state, ViewModel/repository flow, coroutine side effects, navigation arguments, and resource bindings that may be missing or only partially summarized.\n244: \n245: ## Target Architecture Organization\n246: \n247: Use the source project structure as a responsibility guide, then adapt it to\n248: idiomatic HarmonyOS Cangjie modules. Do not mechanically mirror Android\n249: Activity, Fragment, Adapter, BroadcastReceiver, ContentProvider, or XML layout\n250: boundaries, but also do not collapse unrelated domain behavior into broad files\n251: such as `index.cj`, `app_state.cj`, or one all-purpose state module. If\n252: source behavior is scattered only because of Android framework glue, lifecycle,\n253: binding, or layout boundaries, merge it into clearer Cangjie modules when that\n254: improves readability and repairability. Keep single-file LOC and responsibility\n255: scope controlled, and organize production Cangjie code around source business\n256: concepts such as domain models, repositories, data/storage services,\n257: commands/mutations, preferences/security or configuration services, state\n258: stores, and page composition. Thin UIAbility/page shell files may compose these\n259: modules, but they\n260: should not own repository, persistence, security, or mutation logic. For\n261: critical/high coverage entries, prefer targetEndpoints that identify precise\n262: modules or functions instead of only root views, whole files, or grouped state\n263: surfaces.\n264: \n265: ## Coverage And Capability Review\n266: \n267: Use `source-coverage-matrix.json/md` as the feature coverage record and `platform-capability-check.json/md` as the platform capability record. During planning and phase work, update them when target behavior is planned, implemented, tested, replaced, or explicitly deferred. Keep structured `coverageFacts` and `capabilityFacts` aligned with any legacy status/evidence fields you touch. The workflow uses these facts for phase gates, group verdicts, repair queues, and authority validation; explanatory prose is auxiliary and should not be the only place where a required fact appears. For every closed critical/high source feature, record sourceBehavior, targetBehavior, parityLevel, targetEndpoints, and verificationEvidence; use `verification-results.json/md` as supporting evidence, but do not treat a build pass alone as per-feature behavior verification. Avoid marking large groups of behavior deferred or implemented-simplified without concrete source evidence, preserved-behavior explanation, blocker reason, fallback behavior, risk, and future completion path. For critical/high platform capabilities, query CangjieSkills/HarmonyOS/Cangjie API docs and HarmonyOS-Examples before choosing a direct API, platform replacement, fallback, or deferred status. When a third-party package may be needed, also query the Cangjie package index (`https://pkg.cangjie-lang.cn`) or cjpm package lookup. When checking current SDK availability, prefer pure Cangjie `.cj.d`/`.cjo` declarations under `$HOME/.cangjie-sdk/**/cangjie/api/modules` and `$HOME/.cangjie-sdk/**/cangjie/api/lib` before DevEco ETS/JS/native declarations. If a suitable HarmonyOS/Cangjie API, Kit, example, or package exists, implement it or mark it platform-replaced with evidence; do not close the capability with local mock data, in-memory simulation, sample data, or another fallback. Direct target API evidence must be callable from the HarmonyOS Cangjie target. Treat ArkTS `.d.ts` declarations, JS APIs, native C headers/librar... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n268: \n269: ## Strict Coverage Task\n270: \n271: Do not silently omit, stub, or weaken source behavior. Every critical/high feature, resource, platform capability, test obligation, and Compose state, ViewModel/repository flow, coroutine effects path must be implemented, replaced with a justified fallback, or documented as deferred with evidence and risk. Critical/high `implemented-simplified` entries must explain the simplification, preserved user-visible behavior, target endpoint/test evidence, source or platform evidence, parityLevel, targetBehavior, and verificationEvidence.\n272: \n273: ## Source Test Inventory\n274: \n275: The runner found these likely source-side tests or verification assets by path scan:\n276: \n277: - `app/src/androidTest/` (directory)\n278: - `app/src/test/` (directory)\n279: - `app/src/androidTest/java/` (directory)\n280: - `app/src/androidTest/java/com/` (directory)\n281: - `app/src/androidTest/java/com/example/` (directory)\n282: - `app/src/androidTest/java/com/example/foodike/` (directory)\n283: - `app/src/androidTest/java/com/example/foodike/ExampleInstrumentedTest.kt` (file)\n284: - `app/src/test/java/` (directory)\n285: - `app/src/test/java/com/` (directory)\n286: - `app/src/test/java/com/example/` (directory)\n287: - `app/src/test/java/com/example/foodike/` (directory)\n288: - `app/src/test/java/com/example/foodike/ExampleUnitTest.kt` (file)\n289: \n290: Use this inventory as a starting point. It can miss project-specific verification assets, so still inspect the source project during planning before deciding that tests are absent.\n291: \n292: ## Phase 1: Planning\n293: \n294: Generate detailed translation plans:\n295: \n296: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md`: human-readable phase plan, migration strategy, risks, gate criteria, and deferred items.\n297: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.json`: strict JSON structured file, asset, dependency, phase, test, state-machine, group contract, and deferred-item plan.\n298: \n299: Use `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/plan-seed.md` / `.json` as the compact cross-language planning index when present. It summarizes source units, callable method/function/composable/event-handler contracts, UI route/action/state contracts, data/resource/platform capability contracts, phase/group candidates, structure risks, and analysis gaps from Java, Kotlin, mixed Android, or ArkTS inputs. Treat it as planning evidence, not a complete source of truth: inspect source files when behavior is unclear or when source code contradicts static analysis.\n300: \n301: The plan must include `files`, `assets`, `dependencies`, `tests`, `phases`, and `deferred`. For each phase, include canonical phase id, target scope, source evidence, gate command, expected tests, state/data behavior to preserve, and deferred risks. Each phase should also include implementation-group ownership data, either under `implementationGroups` inside the phase or in an equivalent top-level group map. Each group should include stable `groupId`, `title`, `groupType`, `priority`, `sourcePaths`, `sourceMethods` or callable contract references when available, `featureIds`, `resourceInputs`, `platformCapabilityIds`, `uiContracts` or UI route/action/state hints, `dataContracts`, `expectedTargetDomains`, `requiredBehaviors`, `riskHints`, and `acceptanceEvidence`. If static analysis misses or misstates behavior, record an `analysisGaps` or `sourceOverrides` note instead of silently dropping the behavior.\n302: \n303: ## Plan JSON Contract\n304: \n305: `plan.json` must be strict JSON and must include these required top-level keys:\n306: \n307: - `files`\n308: - `assets`\n309: - `dependencies`\n310: - `tests`\n311: - `phases`\n312: - `deferred`\n313: \n314: Extra top-level keys are allowed, but they do not replace the required keys. For\n315: example, `testStrategy` may provide detail, but `tests` must still exist.\n316: Likewise, `platformCapabilityDecisions` may provide detail, but\n317: `dependencies`, `assets`, and `deferred` must still exist when relevant.\n318: \n319: Minimum valid skeleton:\n320: \n321: ```json\n322: {\n323:   \"files\": [],\n324:   \"assets\": [],\n325:   \"dependencies\": [],\n326:   \"tests\": [],\n327:   \"phases\": [\n328:     {\n329:       \"id\": \"phase-01-project-skeleton-resources\",\n330:       \"title\": \"Project skeleton and resources\",\n331:       \"priority\": \"critical\",\n332:       \"targetScope\": [],\n333:       \"sourceEvidence\": [],\n334:       \"requiredInputs\": [],\n335:       \"expectedFiles\": [],\n336:       \"gateCommand\": \"\",\n337:       \"expectedTests\": [],\n338:       \"stateDataBehavior\": [],\n339:       \"deferredRisks\": [],\n340:       \"implementationGroups\": [\n341:         {\n342:           \"groupId\": \"phase-01-bootstrap\",\n343:           \"title\": \"Bootstrap target project\",\n344:           \"groupType\": \"source-behavior\",\n345:           \"priority\": \"critical\",\n346:           \"sourcePaths\": [],\n347:           \"sourceMethods\": [],\n348:           \"featureIds\": [],\n349:           \"resourceInputs\": [],\n350:           \"platformCapabilityIds\": [],\n351:           \"uiContracts\": [],\n352:           \"dataContracts\": [],\n353:           \"expectedTargetDomains\": [],\n354:           \"requiredBehaviors\": [],\n355:           \"riskHints\": [],\n356:           \"acceptanceEvidence\": []\n357:         }\n358:       ]\n359:     }\n360:   ],\n361:   \"deferred\": []\n362: }\n363: ```\n364: \n365: Use canonical phase identifiers such as `phase-01-project-skeleton-resources`.\n366: Each implementation group needs a stable `groupId`, `title`, `groupType`, and\n367: `priority`; bind it to source behavior, resources, capabilities, UI/data\n368: contracts, tests, or acceptance evidence whenever available. If the plan is\n369: large, write this complete valid skeleton first, then expand it in batches while\n370: keeping the file valid strict JSON after every write.\n371: \n372: \n373: Before ending the planning session, validate the planning artifacts with the\n374: platform-appropriate command below:\n375: \n376: POSIX shell:\n377: \n378: ```sh\n379: test -s 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md' && \\\n380:   test -s 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.json' && \\\n381:   'C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe' -m json.tool 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.json' >/dev/null\n382: ```\n383: \n384: Windows PowerShell:\n385: \n386: ```powershell\n387: if (!(Test-Path -LiteralPath 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md' -PathType Leaf)) { exit 1 }\n388: if ((Get-Item -LiteralPath 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md').Length -eq 0) { exit 1 }\n389: if (!(Test-Path -LiteralPath 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.json' -PathType Leaf)) { exit 1 }\n390: if ((Get-Item -LiteralPath 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.json').Length -eq 0) { exit 1 }\n391: & 'C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe' '-m' 'json.tool' 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.json' | Out-Null\n392: ```\n393: \n394: ## Translation Requirements\n395: \n396: - Preserve source behavior rather than file names alone.\n397: - Use source project structure as a responsibility guide while adapting to\n398:   HarmonyOS Cangjie idioms: keep domain/service/state boundaries clear, merge\n399:   source fragments when Cangjie reads better, and avoid overgrown all-purpose\n400:   files.\n401: - Recreate UI layout, navigation, validation, state refresh, transitions, loading/empty/error states, and user-visible side effects as closely as practical.\n402: - Translate resources and resource usages into HarmonyOS Cangjie style resources.\n403: - Copy image assets when valid; convert vector/state drawables or ArkTS resource references into usable HarmonyOS assets or Cangjie state code.\n404: - Replace unsupported Android, Jetpack, Firebase, Google, ArkTS-only, or third-party APIs with HarmonyOS/Cangjie APIs, Kits, packages, or compatible abstractions after checking docs/examples. Use local simulation only when no suitable platform or package capability exists and record the blocker.\n405: - Preserve backend, persistence, CRUD, refresh, observer/recomposition/state semantics recorded in analysis inputs.\n406: - Keep implementation modular; do not collapse the app into one large file.\n407: - Leave future integration points for platform services when local replacements are used.\n408: - Check that the program state machine is still satisfied at the end of each phase.\n409: - Preserve Kotlin app behavior, not just file names or UI appearance.\n410: - Preserve Jetpack Compose behavior when present: composables, state hoisting, remembered state, callbacks, navigation routes, screen parameters, LazyColumn/LazyRow behavior, filtering, search, validation, dialogs, bottom bars, and recomposition-triggering state changes.\n411: - Preserve XML/ViewBinding behavior when present: Activity/Fragment flow, adapters, click listeners, form validation, RecyclerView/ListView refresh behavior, and navigation.\n412: - Preserve ViewModel, StateFlow, LiveData, coroutine, repository, Room, Retrofit, Firebase, DataStore, SharedPreferences, and local cache semantics when present.\n413: - Translate Android resource definitions and Kotlin resource usages into HarmonyOS Cangjie style resources.\n414: - Copy image assets when direct copying is valid.\n415: - Convert Android vector or state drawable resources to usable HarmonyOS assets or Cangjie state code.\n416: - Replace unsupported Android SDK, Firebase SDK, Google SDK, Jetpack, or third-party dependencies with local or HarmonyOS-compatible abstractions.\n417: - Preserve backend, persistence, CRUD, refresh, observable state, and user-visible update semantics recorded in behavior specs.\n418: - For state mutation operations such as add/delete/update/search/filter, ensure the translated Cangjie UI immediately re-renders in the same situations where the Kotlin app recomposes, collects a new Flow value, observes LiveData, or refreshes an adapter.\n419: \n420: ## Test Migration Requirements\n421: \n422: - During planning, inspect the source project for tests such as `src/test`, `src/androidTest`, `test`, `tests`, `ohosTest`, or project-specific verification assets.\n423: - If the source project has tests, migrate or adapt the relevant tests into the target project so they validate translated Cangjie behavior rather than source-platform implementation details.\n424: - If the source project has no tests, generate a modest set of focused target-side tests for core behavior that can be tested without fragile UI automation, such as models, parsers, repositories, settings/preferences, CRUD, search/filtering, validation, state refresh, and important business rules.\n425: - If the source project has too few or shallow tests, add supplemental tests for high-risk translated behavior and any phase-critical data/state logic.\n426: - Prefer automated tests integrated with the target HarmonyOS Cangjie project. If the available SDK/project template does not support a runnable automated test for a behavior, keep the implementation testable, record the limitation, and add the smallest useful test harness or test specification inside the target project.\n427: - Do not delete or disable migrated/generated tests merely to make the build pass. If a test cannot be supported in the current phase, record it as deferred with source evidence, reason, fallback validation, and future completion path.\n428: - Report migrated tests, generated tests, supplemental tests, test commands run, and any deferred test coverage at the end of each phase.\n429: \n430: ## Build Gate Requirement\n431: \n432: After each implementation phase, run the full build gate via:\n433: \n434: ```bash\n435: C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py \\\n436:   --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike \\\n437:   --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony \\\n438:   --phase <phase-name>\n439: ```\n440: \n441: If the build gate fails, read the generated `build-report.md` and `opencode-build-blocker-prompt.txt`, then fix only the current phase blocker before continuing.\n442: \n443: ## Session Discipline\n444: \n445: - Always read the agent protocol before editing.\n446: - Always read `plan.md` and `plan.json` before phase work.\n447: - Do not modify `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`.\n448: - Do not modify `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-records`, workflow scripts, or generated reports other than the agent-maintained source coverage matrix and platform capability check.\n449: - If `apply_patch` fails, read back affected files before retrying.\n450: - At phase end, review contradictions with `plan.md` / `plan.json`, remove unnecessary temporary code, and record deferred issues.\n\n(End of file - total 450 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie Translation Plan\n\n## Goal\n\nTranslate the Android Kotlin project in `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike` into a HarmonyOS Cangjie project rooted at `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`, preserving main features, screen flow, resources, state changes, data behavior, tests, and user-visible side effects while adapting implementation to HarmonyOS Cangjie patterns.\n\n## Paths\n\n- App name: `Foodike`\n- Source kind: `kotlin`\n- Translation workspace: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike`\n- Workspace standing instructions: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\AGENTS.md`\n- Source project: `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`\n- Target HarmonyOS Cangjie project: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`\n- Translation inputs: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs`\n- Translation records: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-records`\n- Agent protocol: `D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md`\n- HarmonyOS Cangjie checklist: `D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\docs\\harmonyos-cangjie-translation-checklist.md`\n\n## Role Split","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"task-planning.md","time":{"start":1782442459639,"end":1782442459643}},"id":"prt_f01d981e3001ESs3BjXs5Gw9vp","sessionID":"ses_0fe26a9d2ffer6h4jq2UJwr0EY","messageID":"msg_f01d97082001dRI2jVD22scUf4"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782442459666,"sessionID":"ses_0fe26a9d2ffer6h4jq2UJwr0EY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_0yxwFj0iKmHLLrZfEVcolNVs","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md"},"output":"<path>D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Foodike HarmonyOS Cangjie Migration Plan\n2: \n3: ## Scope\n4: \n5: - Source project: `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`\n6: - Target project: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`\n7: - Session type: planning only\n8: - Source app shape: single-module Jetpack Compose app with splash-gated startup, Compose navigation, static fixture-backed content, and DataStore-backed login persistence.\n9: \n10: ## Confirmed Source Behavior\n11: \n12: - Startup uses `SplashViewModel` plus Android splash screen keep-on-screen behavior to resolve the first route before showing the app shell.\n13: - Initial route is `onboarding` when login state is false and `home` when login state is true.\n14: - Navigation shell owns the nav controller, a shared list scroll state, a floating cart button, and conditional bottom-bar visibility.\n15: - Onboarding is a three-page pager with next-step progression and final navigation to login.\n16: - Login stores only a boolean logged-in flag. Valid credentials are hard-coded to `abcxyz@gmail.com` and `abcdef`; invalid login emits a snackbar.\n17: - Home loads ads, recommended food cards, restaurant lists, and favourites from repositories. Selecting a restaurant stores the active restaurant in session state before navigating to detail.\n18: - History reads liked restaurants from the same session repository and also stores the selected restaurant before navigating to detail.\n19: - Restaurant detail reads the selected restaurant, derives recommended/non-veg/veg menu sections, toggles section expansion and local liked state, and shows the floating cart button only when the summed local item count is non-zero.\n20: - Cart currently reads repository cart snapshots but keeps bill totals, delivery restaurant, item-note editor, and quantity buttons mostly as local UI behavior with no persistent mutation wiring.\n21: - Profile shows static profile information and toggles the persisted login state on logout before clearing navigation history back to onboarding.\n22: - Real persistence is limited to login state. Restaurant selection, favourites, menu counts, liked state, and cart snapshots are in-memory session state only.\n23: \n24: ## Static Analysis Overrides\n25: \n26: - Generated platform-capability heuristics over-report media library, SAF/file access, runtime permissions, and notification/widget behavior. Source walkthrough evidence shows no actual media picker, external storage, SAF, dangerous permission request, service, receiver, widget, or notification flow in the app.\n27: - `Navigation.kt` contains a duplicated onboarding destination entry. Planning keeps the intended destination set but treats the duplicate as source cleanup noise, not a required user-visible behavior.\n28: - `SearchBar`, `ChipBar`, `MenuItemCard`, `ItemSection`, and some cart/detail interactions are currently local UI state only. They still matter for parity because the visible counters, filter chips, and note editors update immediately in-place.\n29: \n30: ## Target Architecture\n31: \n32: Plan the HarmonyOS Cangjie target around business domains instead of mirroring every Compose file one-for-one:\n33: \n34: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/app/` for app shell, startup, and route composition.\n35: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/domain/` for immutable models and route-safe view data.\n36: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/data/` for fixture loading, session repository logic, and preference-backed login state.\n37: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/features/onboarding|login|home|history|detail|cart|profile/` for feature stores and page composition.\n38: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/common/` for reusable widgets, formatting helpers, and resource adapters.\n39: - `entry/src/main/resources/base/` plus `AppScope/resources/` for strings, colors, images, app icon, startup visuals, and page profile wiring.\n40: \n41: Thin ability/page shell files may compose feature stores, but they should not absorb repository or preference logic.\n42: \n43: ## Phase Plan\n44: \n45: ### Phase 1: `phase-01-project-skeleton-resources`\n46: \n47: - Goal: bootstrap the HarmonyOS entry module, resource tree, startup wiring, and domain/data skeleton.\n48: - Key outputs:\n49:   - Target entry module from the mapcir skeleton.\n50:   - AppScope and entry metadata files.\n51:   - Core domain models.\n52:   - Resource catalog for strings, colors, and media copied/adapted from source drawables and mipmaps.\n53:   - Placeholder service boundaries for fixture content and persisted login state.\n54: - Gate:\n55:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-01-project-skeleton-resources`\n56: - Review focus:\n57:   - Entry package normalization to `ohos_app_cangjie_entry`.\n58:   - App icon, startup resources, and base strings exist.\n59:   - No broad shell file owns all business logic.\n60: \n61: ### Phase 2: `phase-02-startup-navigation-session`\n62: \n63: - Goal: implement startup route resolution, persisted login state, and the shared application shell.\n64: - Key outputs:\n65:   - Preference-backed login state service.\n66:   - Startup/session store that resolves first route before page composition.\n67:   - App navigation host with onboarding, login, home, history, cart, profile, and detail routes.\n68:   - Shared bottom-bar and floating cart-button shell behavior, including route and scroll gating.\n69: - Gate:\n70:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-02-startup-navigation-session`\n71: - Review focus:\n72:   - Startup does not flash the wrong initial page.\n73:   - Login/logout mutations immediately change visible navigation behavior.\n74:   - Route ownership remains separate from data services.\n75: \n76: ### Phase 3: `phase-03-onboarding-login-profile`\n77: \n78: - Goal: land the onboarding, login, and profile user flows with persisted session semantics.\n79: - Key outputs:\n80:   - Three-page onboarding sequence with progress indicators and next/final navigation behavior.\n81:   - Login form state, hard-coded credential validation, snackbar error path, and successful login transition to home.\n82:   - Profile page sections, static profile visuals, and logout mutation that clears the shell stack to onboarding.\n83: - Gate:\n84:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-03-onboarding-login-profile`\n85: - Review focus:\n86:   - Login failure messaging remains immediate and non-blocking.\n87:   - Persisted login state survives app restart semantics.\n88:   - Placeholder social/signup/profile edit actions are visibly retained as non-implemented affordances, not silently removed.\n89: \n90: ### Phase 4: `phase-04-home-history-discovery`\n91: \n92: - Goal: implement fixture-backed discovery screens and restaurant selection flow.\n93: - Key outputs:\n94:   - Fixture content repository and session repository.\n95:   - Home screen sections for top bar, greeting, search bar, ads, recommended cards, favourites, filters, and restaurant list.\n96:   - History page with tab state and favourite restaurant selection flow.\n97:   - Shared selection command that stores the current restaurant before detail navigation.\n98: - Gate:\n99:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-04-home-history-discovery`\n100: - Review focus:\n101:   - Favourite sections render only when non-empty.\n102:   - Filter chips and search bar preserve immediate local-state updates.\n103:   - Selection and navigation happen in the same order as the source: save restaurant first, then navigate.\n104: \n105: ### Phase 5: `phase-05-detail-cart-state-mutations`\n106: \n107: - Goal: implement restaurant detail, menu section expansion, local quantity controls, and cart rendering semantics.\n108: - Key outputs:\n109:   - Detail store fed by session-selected restaurant and repository snapshots.\n110:   - Recommended/non-veg/veg section grouping with expandable headers and icon rotation semantics.\n111:   - Local liked toggle state.\n112:   - Menu item quantity controls with immediate UI updates.\n113:   - Floating cart button visibility driven by non-zero summed item counts.\n114:   - Cart page sections for selected items, note editor, coupon input shell, delivery card, and bill section.\n115: - Gate:\n116:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-05-detail-cart-state-mutations`\n117: - Review focus:\n118:   - Immediate visible updates for expansion toggles, add/subtract controls, and note text.\n119:   - Detail-to-cart routing is preserved.\n120:   - Any simplification between local detail quantity state and repository cart state must be documented explicitly in coverage records if retained.\n121: \n122: ### Phase 6: `phase-06-polish-tests-verification`\n123: \n124: - Goal: close resource gaps, add focused tests, and verify high-risk behavior before row-level coverage backfill.\n125: - Key outputs:\n126:   - Target tests for session persistence, startup route resolution, login validation, route selection commands, and pure state reducers/helpers.\n127:   - Resource completeness check for missing strings and media references.\n128:   - Final build-gate evidence and any explicit deferred items recorded with risk.\n129: - Gate:\n130:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-06-polish-tests-verification`\n131: - Review focus:\n132:   - No unresolved string/media references.\n133:   - Target tests verify behavior that source tests did not cover.\n134:   - Coverage and capability backfill can proceed narrowly from the completed plan.\n135: \n136: ## Test Strategy\n137: \n138: - Source tests are only boilerplate examples and do not cover app behavior.\n139: - Add target-side tests for:\n140:   - login preference persistence and startup destination resolution\n141:   - login credential validation and snackbar error emission\n142:   - restaurant-selection command behavior\n143:   - detail section expansion and floating-cart visibility state\n144:   - filter helper mapping and any extracted formatting helpers\n145: - Prefer `cjpm test` where the target template supports it. If the HarmonyOS template blocks runnable tests, keep logic in small pure modules and record the exact harness limitation before relying on compile-only evidence.\n146: \n147: ## Resource Plan\n148: \n149: - Migrate all 52 source strings into HarmonyOS string resources before feature-complete review.\n150: - Copy and adapt all referenced bitmap/vector assets used by onboarding, login, cards, icons, splash, and app icon.\n151: - Convert Android theme values into HarmonyOS startup colors and page token resources.\n152: - Preserve content descriptions and user-facing labels where they are visible or accessibility-relevant.\n153: \n154: ## Platform Capability Decisions For Planning\n155: \n156: - Persisted preferences/login state: required and should map to a direct HarmonyOS preference/storage API.\n157: - Startup splash behavior: required, but exact API may be platform-replaced with HarmonyOS startup-page behavior if direct splash parity differs.\n158: - Localization resources: required and should map to HarmonyOS resource bundles.\n159: - Runtime permissions: currently not source-backed as a real user flow; keep as a reviewed capability row but do not plan first-phase implementation work for it.\n160: - Media library, SAF/file access, notifications/widgets: currently not source-backed; keep these out of active implementation scope unless later source inspection contradicts the walkthrough.\n161: \n162: ## Missing Inputs\n163: \n164: - `translation-inputs/plan-validation-report.md` and `.json` are missing.\n165: - `translation-inputs/phase-task-checklist.md` and `.json` are missing.\n166: - `translation-inputs/phase-capability-checklist.md` and `.json` are missing.\n167: - `translation-inputs/test-build-reports/` is missing.\n168: - Several Kotlin sidecar summaries listed in `task-planning.md` are missing, but the primary Kotlin analysis, locations, Android analysis, walkthrough, and source inspection were sufficient for planning.\n169: - `translation-inputs/mapcir/skeleton-hybrid/` is missing; the plain skeleton is present and sufficient for bootstrap planning.\n170: \n171: ## Deferred Risks\n172: \n173: - The source cart/detail mutation model is inconsistent: quantity changes are local to `MenuItemCard`, while cart data comes from a separate in-memory repository snapshot. Target implementation should preserve visible behavior first, but the final parity record may require an `implemented-simplified` note unless this mismatch is harmonized carefully.\n174: - Source search and chip filters currently keep local UI state without repository filtering logic. Removing them would be a regression, but over-implementing new filtering semantics would also diverge from source behavior.\n175: - Static analysis still tags many files with permissions/file/media concerns that are not source-backed. Coverage and platform records should be updated later with source-evidence notes to avoid false implementation pressure.\n176: - The target project is currently empty; phase 1 must establish a valid entry module before any row-level planned-phase backfill can safely validate target endpoints.\n\n(End of file - total 176 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Foodike HarmonyOS Cangjie Migration Plan\n\n## Scope\n\n- Source project: `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`\n- Target project: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`\n- Session type: planning only\n- Source app shape: single-module Jetpack Compose app with splash-gated startup, Compose navigation, static fixture-backed content, and DataStore-backed login persistence.\n\n## Confirmed Source Behavior\n\n- Startup uses `SplashViewModel` plus Android splash screen keep-on-screen behavior to resolve the first route before showing the app shell.\n- Initial route is `onboarding` when login state is false and `home` when login state is true.\n- Navigation shell owns the nav controller, a shared list scroll state, a floating cart button, and conditional bottom-bar visibility.\n- Onboarding is a three-page pager with next-step progression and final navigation to login.\n- Login stores only a boolean logged-in flag. Valid credentials are hard-coded to `abcxyz@gmail.com` and `abcdef`; invalid login emits a snackbar.\n- Home loads ads, recommended food cards, restaurant lists, and favourites from repositories. Selecting a restaurant stores the active restaurant in session state before navigating to detail.\n- History reads liked restaurants from the same session repository and also stores the selected restaurant before navigating to detail.\n- Restaurant detail reads the selected restaurant, derives recommended/non-veg/veg menu sections, toggles section expansion and local liked state, and shows the floating cart button only when the summed local item count is non-zero.\n- Cart currently reads repository cart snapshots but keeps bill totals, delivery restaurant, item-note editor, and quantity buttons mostly as local UI behavior with no persistent mutation wiring.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"plan.md","time":{"start":1782442459661,"end":1782442459665}},"id":"prt_f01d981f8001Vkc6ilx3MRjPrG","sessionID":"ses_0fe26a9d2ffer6h4jq2UJwr0EY","messageID":"msg_f01d97082001dRI2jVD22scUf4"}}
